#: ../pep-0376.txt:17
msgid "Abstract"
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:19
msgid ""
"The goal of this PEP is to provide a standard infrastructure to manage "
"project distributions installed on a system, so all tools that are "
"installing or removing projects are interoperable."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:23
msgid ""
"To achieve this goal, the PEP proposes a new format to describe installed "
"distributions on a system. It also describes a reference implementation for "
"the standard library."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:27
msgid ""
"In the past an attempt was made to create an installation database (see :pep:"
"`262`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:30
msgid "Combined with :pep:`345`, the current proposal supersedes :pep:`262`."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:32
msgid ""
"Note: the implementation plan didn't go as expected, so it should be "
"considered informative only for this PEP."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:37
msgid "Rationale"
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:39
msgid ""
"There are two problems right now in the way distributions are installed in "
"Python:"
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:42
msgid ""
"There are too many ways to do it and this makes interoperation difficult."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:43
msgid "There is no API to get information on installed distributions."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:46
msgid "How distributions are installed"
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:48
msgid ""
"Right now, when a distribution is installed in Python, every element can be "
"installed in a different directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:51
msgid ""
"For instance, ``Distutils`` installs the pure Python code in the ``purelib`` "
"directory, which is ``lib/python2.6/site-packages`` for unix-like systems "
"and Mac OS X, or ``Lib\\site-packages`` under Python's installation "
"directory for Windows."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:56
msgid ""
"Additionally, the ``install_egg_info`` subcommand of the Distutils "
"``install`` command adds an ``.egg-info`` file for the project into the "
"``purelib`` directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:60
msgid ""
"For example, for the ``docutils`` distribution, which contains one package "
"an extra module and executable scripts, three elements are installed in "
"``site-packages``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:64
msgid "``docutils``: The ``docutils`` package."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:65
msgid "``roman.py``: An extra module used by ``docutils``."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:66
msgid ""
"``docutils-0.5-py2.6.egg-info``: A file containing the distribution metadata "
"as described in :pep:`314`. This file corresponds to the file called ``PKG-"
"INFO``, built by the ``sdist`` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:70
msgid ""
"Some executable scripts, such as ``rst2html.py``, are also added in the "
"``bin`` directory of the Python installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:73
msgid ""
"Another project called ``setuptools`` [#setuptools]_ has two other formats "
"to install distributions, called ``EggFormats`` [#eggformats]_:"
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:76
msgid ""
"a self-contained ``.egg`` directory, that contains all the distribution "
"files and the distribution metadata in a file called ``PKG-INFO`` in a "
"subdirectory called ``EGG-INFO``. ``setuptools`` creates other files in that "
"directory that can be considered as complementary metadata."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:81
msgid ""
"an ``.egg-info`` directory installed in ``site-packages``, that contains the "
"same files ``EGG-INFO`` has in the ``.egg`` format."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:84
msgid ""
"The first format is automatically used when you install a distribution that "
"uses the ``setuptools.setup`` function in its setup.py file, instead of the "
"``distutils.core.setup`` one."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:88
msgid ""
"``setuptools`` also add a reference to the distribution into an ``easy-"
"install.pth`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:91
msgid ""
"Last, the ``setuptools`` project provides an executable script called "
"``easy_install`` [#easyinstall]_ that installs all distributions, including "
"distutils-based ones in self-contained ``.egg`` directories."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:95
msgid ""
"If you want to have standalone ``.egg-info`` directories for your "
"distributions, e.g. the second ``setuptools`` format, you have to force it "
"when you work with a setuptools-based distribution or with the "
"``easy_install`` script. You can force it by using the ``--single-version-"
"externally-managed`` option **or** the ``--root`` option. This will make the "
"``setuptools`` project install the project like distutils does."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:102
msgid "This option is used by :"
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:104
msgid "the ``pip`` [#pip]_ installer"
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:105
msgid "the Fedora packagers [#fedora]_."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:106
msgid "the Debian packagers [#debian]_."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:109
msgid "Uninstall information"
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:111
msgid ""
"Distutils doesn't provide an ``uninstall`` command. If you want to uninstall "
"a distribution, you have to be a power user and remove the various elements "
"that were installed, and then look over the ``.pth`` file to clean them if "
"necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:116
msgid ""
"And the process differs depending on the tools you have used to install the "
"distribution and if the distribution's ``setup.py`` uses Distutils or "
"Setuptools."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:120
msgid ""
"Under some circumstances, you might not be able to know for sure that you "
"have removed everything, or that you didn't break another distribution by "
"removing a file that is shared among several distributions."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:124
msgid ""
"But there's a common behavior: when you install a distribution, files are "
"copied in your system. And it's possible to keep track of these files for "
"later removal."
msgstr ""

#: ../pep-0376.txt:128
msgid ""
"Moreover, the Pip project has gained an ``uninstall`` feature lately. It "
"records all installed files, using the ``record`` option of the ``install`` "
"command."
msgstr ""

